Day 9 : 1st October Elastic Load Balancing
An Ecommerce Site's Servers are going to be down. How to fix this.

Create 3 instances with port 80 enabled.

____________
@ Web-one @
____________

#yum install httpd -y
#cd /var/www/html/
#echo "This is my server-one" > index.html
#ll
#systemctl start httpd
#systemctl enable httpd
#curl http://localhost

____________
@ Web-two @
____________

#yum install httpd -y
#cd /var/www/html/
#echo "This is my server-one" > index.html
#ll
#systemctl start httpd
#systemctl enable httpd
#curl http://localhost

____________
@ Web-three @
____________

#yum install httpd -y
#cd /var/www/html/
#echo "This is my server-one" > index.html
#ll
#systemctl start httpd
#systemctl enable httpd
#curl http://localhost

->Copy Public IP of the instances and paste along with :80

->Target Group > Collection of servers
> Create Target group
 > target type - instance
 > my LBTG
 > Next > Select instances > Include

Load Balancers > Create App Load Balancer
 > give name
 > Scheme : Internet-facing
 > Availability Zones and subnets : select subnets
 > Security Group
 > Listening port 80
 > Target Group

Copy DNS Name > Paste in new tab
-> Stop any Instance -> The Load Blancer will do it's work

______________
Auto Scaling
______________


> Create Launch Template 
 name -asg template
 desc - this is for testing

key pair
subnet 1 a
sg group
advance > User Data >

>create Auto Scaling Group
name > template > next > VPC > subnets : a,b,c > Balanced best effort > next
> Load Balancer
> NO VPC Lattice

Health Checks > Elastic Load balancing health checks

Desired Capacity : 2

Scaling > min - 1 : max - 5

Automatic scaling - optional
> Target tracking
 target value 75
> instance warmup - 180

Add notifications

> next > next

Create autoscaling group
Remember to delete autoscaling group
Then Delete Instance


